body:
Hey @Stalex89,

It's normal that we don't have `__isArtificial` as the package is made to render actual received results.

The problem is that `useInstantSearch` does not wait for the results, only `use*` (* being any widget) do, so that's why you receive `__isArtificial`.

Probably `useInstantSearch` should wait for proper results, but in the meantime can you try to replace your SearchNoResultsBoundary with this (it's a bit hacky) : 
```tsx
const SearchNoResultsBoundary = ({
  children,
  fallback = <NoResults />,
}: Props) => {
  // This is just to wait for actual results as `useInstantSearch` does not
  useSearchBox();

  const { results } = useInstantSearch();

  if (!results.__isArtificial && results.nbHits === 0) {
    return (
      <>
        {fallback}
        <div hidden>{children}</div>
      </>
    );
  }

  return children;
};
```

We basically just added a `useSearchBox` call before without using the returned values, but it could be any other hook.
With this `__isArtificial` will always be `undefined` on the server, as it should. It should still work fine for CSR too. Tell me how it goes !

Hi @aymeric-giraudet, your suggestion fixes the UI error, thank you very much for you response!

I've doublechecked my code again, especially the part where I'm [detecting the empty query results and returning the formatted response](https://www.algolia.com/doc/guides/building-search-ui/going-further/conditional-requests/react/#detecting-empty-search-requests):

```
const searchClient = algoliaClient
  ? {
      ...algoliaClient,
      search(requests: any) {
        if (requests.every(({ params }: any) => !params.query)) {
          return Promise.resolve({
            results: requests.map(() => ({
              hits: [],
              nbHits: 0,
              nbPages: 0,
              page: 0,
              processingTimeMS: 0,
              hitsPerPage: 0,
              exhaustiveNbHits: false,
              query: "",
              params: "",
            })),
          });
        }
        return algoliaClient.search(requests);
      },
    }
  : null;
```
I've noticed that I'm not returning the `__isArtificial` flag here, so it's not present in the client and therefore causes the UI render to be different from server (thought it's not in the docs as well).

adding the `__isArtificial: true` to the response seems to fix my issue:

```
const searchClient = algoliaClient
  ? {
      ...algoliaClient,
      search(requests: any) {
        if (requests.every(({ params }: any) => !params.query)) {
          return Promise.resolve({
            results: requests.map(() => ({
              hits: [],
              ...
              __isArtificial: true,
            })),
          });
        }
        return algoliaClient.search(requests);
      },
    }
  : null;
```

Thank you again for your help! I will mark this issue as closed.
